693. passura bis ignem] viZ. both in the kiln and in the baking. It is remarkable that the Romans treated their bread-corn nearly as we treat malt,-—they dried it in a kiln before grinding it. The latter art was but

rudely performed, and would have been difficult if the

grain had been moist and clammy. See inf. ii. 520, seqq„ Georg. i. 267, ‘nunc torrete igni fruges, nunc frangite saxo.' nius, quoted on ver. 645. It was vowed by A. Postu- mius, B. c. 498, in consequence of the aid rendered by the twin deities at the battle of Lake Regillus. See Livy, ii. 42.
